<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-895-860  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 895 860.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telephony  Nov 6 1989 v217 n20 p54(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The digital transformation of the local loop. (fiber opticcable)(includes glossary) (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Pitchford, Mark.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Technology, economics, demographics and subscriber demand combineto determine the rate at which local loops become digital andfiber optics becomes the medium of choice.andP;  Although the US has animmense embedded base of analog loop facilities, demand fordigital services eventually will force digitalization of allsubscriber loops.andP;  Digital and analog loops must coexist into thenext century.andP;  Current facility design for analog loops is a majorimpediment to conversion.andP;  Although integration technologies arelimited, integrated DLC systems are cost effective.andP;  The nextgeneration will have systems that conform to a synchronous opticalnetwork (SONET) standard, as well as a time-slot interchanger andsoftware control.andP;  Copper installations forestall necessary worktoward fiber optics.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     TelecommunicationsOutlookGrowthTelephone systemsDigital communicationsTelephone companies.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Evolving loop architectures. (chart)Universal digital channel. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>